04146nam a22006255i 9780226470276DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264702767 a10.7208/97802264702762doi  a(DE-B1597)523964  a(OCoLC)988326285  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aGV715b.T379 2018 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a306.4832231 aTarver, Erin C., eauthor.14aThe I in Team :bSports Fandom and the Reproduction of Identity /cErin C. Tarver. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Sports Fandom and Identity -- t1. Who Is a Fan? -- t2. Sports Fandom as Practice of Subjectivization -- t3. Putting the "We" in "We're Number One": Mascots, Team, and Community Identity -- t4. Hero or Mascot? Fantasies of Identifi cation -- t5. "Honey Badger Takes What He Wants": Southern Collegiate Athletics and the Mascotting of Black Masculinity -- t6. From Mascot to Danger -- t7. Women on the Margins of Sports Fandom -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is one sound that will always be loudest in sports. It isn't the squeak of sneakers or the crunch of helmets; it isn't the grunts or even the stadium music. It's the deafening roar of sports fans. For those few among us on the outside, sports fandom-with its war paint and pennants, its pricey cable TV packages and esoteric stats reeled off like code-looks highly irrational, entertainment gone overboard. But as Erin C. Tarver demonstrates in this book, sports fandom has become extraordinarily important to our psyche, a matter of the very essence of who we are.             Why in the world, Tarver asks, would anyone care about how well a total stranger can throw a ball, or hit one with a bat, or toss one through a hoop? Because such activities and the massive public events that surround them form some of the most meaningful ritual identity practices we have today. They are a primary way we-as individuals and a collective-decide both who we are who we are not. And as such, they are also one of the key ways that various social structures-such as race and gender hierarchies-are sustained, lending a dark side to the joys of being a sports fan. Drawing on everything from philosophy to sociology to sports history, she offers a profound exploration of the significance of sports in contemporary life, showing us just how high the stakes of the game are.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aFans (Persons)zUnited States. 0aIdentity (Psychology) 0aSports spectatorszUnited States. 4aMichel Foucault. 4acommunity. 4afeminist philosophy. 4agender. 4aidentity. 4aphilosophy of sport. 4arace. 4asport in America. 4asports fans. 4asubjectivization. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226470276423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226470276.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles